\subsection{}

In this first formalisation of the concept of analyticity we construe a truth conditional semantics as a function which for any sentence delivers the property of conditions which is true of those conditions under which the sentence is true.

A sentence is analytic if its value under the semantics is that property of conditions which is always true. 
The `conditions' here should be thought of as factual {\it states of affairs} each condition encapsulating one possible complete account of what the (empirical) facts are.
An analytic sentence is then a sentence which is true whatever the conditions.

